If docker is not running see the error:

sudo journalctl -xeu docker.service
sudo dockerd --debug
sudo systemctl stop docker
ip link show | grep docker
sudo ip link delete docker0
sudo rm -rf /var/lib/docker/network



sudo systemctl status docker

Docker architecture
Dockerfile â†’ Image â†’ Container


Dockerfile: Recipe to build the image

Image: Read-only snapshot

Container: Running instance of the image

ðŸ”¹ Layers & caching:

Each Dockerfile instruction creates a layer

Layers are cached â†’ rebuild is faster

| Aspect  | Image      | Container     |
| ------- | ---------- | ------------- |
| State   | Read-only  | Read/write    |
| Start   | Build once | Run many      |
| Storage | Disk       | Memory + Disk |

docker ps          # Running containers
docker ps -a       # All containers
docker stop <name> # Stop container
docker rm <name>   # Remove container

Docker Hub

Public registry for images

Pull prebuilt images, e.g., nginx, node, mongo

Push your own images after building

docker pull nginx
docker push myusername/myimage:tag

TO CHECK RUNNING PROCESS:
sudo lsof -i :3000


DOCKER:
create a simple nestjs app
install package.json
npm run start:dev


1)create a docker file

2)Build the Docker image
docker build -t nestjs-app .
-t nestjs-app â†’ tag for your image

. â†’ current folder (Dockerfile location)

3)docker images
shows the created images

4)Run the container
docker run -d -p 3000:3000 --name nestjs-container nestjs-app

-d â†’ run in background

-p 3000:3000 â†’ host:container port mapping

--name â†’ give a friendly name
nestjs-container --setting container name
nestjs-app: image name that needs to run

Step 5 â€” Check logs
docker logs nestjs-container


Useful for debugging runtime errors inside container
